  "notes": "Received Pronunciation (RP) — traditional prestige accent of England. NON-RHOTIC: /r/ deleted before consonants and word-finally. TRAP-BATH split: BATH words = /ɑː/ (castle, grass, dance). LOT = /ɒ/ (rounded); GOAT = /əʊ/. T-glottaling common in contemporary RP (glottal stop for /t/ word-finally). Source: Wells (1982) vol. 1–2, Cruttenden (2014). C/G SOFTENING: c→[s] and g→[dʒ] before e/i/y (city, gem); exceptions: get, give, girl retain [ɡ]. INTERVOCALIC s: [z] between vowels (rose, nose) but [s] word-initially. TH DISTINCTION: [θ] in content words, [ð] in function words and intervocalically. X WORD-INITIAL: [z] (xylophone) vs [ks] elsewhere. SILENT FINAL E: orthographic word-final <e> after a consonant is not pronounced (mate, hope, time, judge); it historically marked the preceding vowel as tense/long, but that vowel-quality shift is not encoded here because the engine's positional model has no lookback to the preceding nucleus (known engine-limit exception). A small closed class of function words spelled with a genuinely pronounced final <e> (the, be, he, me, we, she) is carved out via `word_exceptions`, since the blanket positional rule cannot distinguish these monosyllables from the regular silent-e pattern. TION/SION FAMILY: -tion/-cian -> [ʃən], -ssion -> [ʃən] (mission, passion; matched via the dedicated `ssion` grapheme so maximal-munch tokenization picks it over `sion`), -sion -> [ʒən] after a vowel (vision, division, decision) or [ʃən] after a consonant (tension, pension, mansion), modelled with the `sion` entry in `positional_graphemes` using AFTER_VOWEL/AFTER_CONSONANT context, -tial/-cial -> [ʃəl], -cious/-tious -> [ʃəs] (Cruttenden 2014 spelling-to-sound correspondence rules). LEXICAL STRESS: word stress is lexically contrastive (record noun vs. record verb) and not reliably orthography-predictable the way Romance penult/final stress endings are, so no declarative `stress` block is encoded (research-tier stress exemption per docs/quality_tiers.md; stress is left to downstream lexical lookup rather than a spelling rule).",
